        <premise ref="A X B1"><md><mrow>2x-y\amp=0</mrow><mrow>-3x+y\amp=0</mrow></md></premise>
        <premise ref="A X B2"><md><mrow>2x-y\amp=5</mrow><mrow>-3x+y\amp=2</mrow></md></premise>
        <premise ref="A X1 B2"><md><mrow>2x_1-x_2\amp=5</mrow><mrow>-3x_1+x_2\amp=2</mrow></md></premise>
        <response xml:id="A" order="2"><m>A=\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -1 \\ -3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m></response>
        <response xml:id="X" order="5"><m>X=\begin{bmatrix}x\\y\end{bmatrix}</m></response>
        <response xml:id="X1" order="6"><m>X=\begin{bmatrix}x_1\\x_2\end{bmatrix}</m></response>
        <response xml:id="Arref" order="4"><m>A=\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp -1 \amp 5 \\ -3 \amp 1\amp 2 \end{bmatrix}</m></response>
        <response xml:id="B1" order="3"><m>B=\begin{bmatrix}0\\0\end{bmatrix}</m></response>
        <response xml:id="B2" order="1"><m>B=\begin{bmatrix}5\\2\end{bmatrix}</m></response>
      </matching>
    </exercise>
    <p>
      Writing linear systems in terms of matrix multiplication raises a new question: how can we solve a linear system that is written
      in the form <m>AX=B</m>?
    </p>
     <p>
        We take our inspiration from the usual algebra of numbers.  If <m>a, b</m> and <m>x</m> 
        are numbers and <m>a\neq 0</m>, 
        then we solve the equation <m>ax=b</m> by
        dividing both sides by <m>a</m> and get
        <me>
        x = \frac{b}{a}
        </me>.
        We do this precisely because <m>\frac{1}{a}\cdot a=1</m>, so writing out more details would give us
        <md>
          <mrow>ax \amp= b </mrow>
          <mrow>\frac{1}{a}\cdot ax \amp= \frac{1}{a}\cdot b </mrow>
          <mrow>1x \amp= \frac{1}{a}\cdot b </mrow>
          <mrow>x \amp= \frac{1}{a}\cdot b = \frac{b}{a}</mrow>
        </md>.
        The key feature is that <m>\frac{1}{a}</m> is the thing we multiply by <m>a</m> to get <m>1</m>; 
        to solve a linear system <m>AX=B</m>, we'll want to do something analogous for matrices. 
        We sometimes call <m>\frac{1}{a}</m> the <em>multiplicative inverse</em> of <m>a</m>, and we know
        that <m>\frac{1}{a}=a^{-1}</m> if written as an exponent. We will use this same language and notation
        for matrices as well.  
    </p>
    <p>
        In <xref ref="identityexercise"/>, we learned about the identity matrix <m>I</m> that
        acts like the number <m>1</m> for square matrices.  For example, the identity matrix of size <m>3</m>
        is <m>\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>, and then
        if <m>A</m> is any <m>3\times 3</m> matrix, then
        <me>
        I A =  A I =  A
        </me>.
        Similarly for the identity matrix of size <m>2</m>, which is <m>\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
        and any <m>2\times 2</m> matrix.
      </p> 
      <p>
        If we had a matrix <m>A^{-1}</m> such that <m>A^{-1} A= I</m>,
        then by analogy to our algebra example above it seems like we might be able to solve the linear system
        <m>A X = B</m> for <m>X</m> by multiplying both sides of the equation by <m>A^{-1}</m>.
        That is,
        <md>
          <mrow>AX \amp= B \amp \amp </mrow>
          <mrow>A^{-1} AX \amp= A^{-1} B \amp \amp \amp \amp \text{multiply both sides on the left by }A^{-1} </mrow>
          <mrow>(A^{-1} A)X \amp= A^{-1} B \amp \amp \amp \amp\text{matrix multiplication is associative} </mrow>
          <mrow>IX \amp= A^{-1}B \amp \amp \amp \amp\text{because }A^{-1}A=I</mrow>
          <mrow>X \amp= A^{-1}B \amp \amp \amp \amp\text{because }IX=X</mrow>
        </md>.
        It seems that we might be able to solve linear systems using matrix multiplication and inverses
        instead of row reducing.
    </p>
    <p>
        Of course, there are some differences between matrix multiplication and number multiplication,
        as we explored throughout <xref ref="ws-matrixmultiplication" text="custom">Matrix Multiplication Participate</xref>, 
        and one consequence is that we 
        aren't guaranteed that a matrix acting like <m>A^{-1}</m> exists for every square matrix <m>A</m>.
        For the <m>2\times 2</m> matrices that arise from two-variable linear systems, it is straightforward to tell
        when <m>A^{-1}</m> exists.  
    </p>
  <definition xml:id="def_inverse"><title>Invertible Matrices and the Inverse of A</title><idx><h>matrix</h><h>inverse</h></idx>
            <idx><h>inverse</h><h>definition</h></idx>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>A</m> be an <m>n\times n</m> matrix.  If there exists an
        <m>n\times n</m> matrix <m>C</m> such that <m>A C = I = C A</m>, then
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>A</m> is <term>invertible</term>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>C</m> is the <term>multiplicative inverse</term>, or just <term>inverse</term>,
              of <m>A</m>, denoted by <m>A^{-1}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Furthermore, if <m>A</m> is a <m>2 \times 2</m> matrix
              <me>
                A = \left[\begin{array}{cc} a\amp b\\c\amp d \end{array} \right]
              </me>,
              the matrix <m>A^{-1}</m> exists precisely when <m>ad-bc\neq 0</m> and then
              <me>
                A^{-1} = \frac{1}{ad-bc}\left[\begin{array}{cc} d\amp -b\\-c\amp a \end{array} \right]
              </me>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
        Note that there are many matrices <m>A</m> where there is no matrix that
        can be multiplied by <m>A</m> to get the identity matrix; in this case, we 
        say that <m>A</m> is <em>not invertible.</em>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    We can't divide by <m>0</m>, so if <m>ad-bc=0</m>, we don't have an inverse.
  </p>
  <example><title>A Matrix Without An Inverse</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Recall <xref ref="exercisenoninvertibleA"/>, where
        <me>
          A = \left[\begin{array}{cc} 1\amp 2\\-2\amp -4 \end{array} \right]
        </me>.
        Here, <m>ad-bc = 1(-4) - 2(-2) = 0</m> and so <m>A</m> doesn't have an inverse.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is why multiplying by <m>A</m> in that exercise didn't act like multiplying by a number does;
        every nonzero number <m>a</m> has an inverse <m>\frac{1}{a}</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
  <!-- interactive question.  Give matrix, ask for entries, a, d, then b, c, then ad-bc, then [d -b \\ -c a] -->
   <exercise label="partsof2by2matrix"><title>Identifying Key Parts for an Inverse</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        The formula for the inverse of any <m>2\times 2</m> matrix depends on viewing the matrix in the form
        <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>.
        Let <me>A=\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 2 \\ 3 \amp 4 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <task label="partsof2by2matrix-a">>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Identify the values of <m>a</m> and <m>d</m> for the matrix <m>A</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a=1</m> and <m>d=2</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              For a matrix described by <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
              the entry <m>a</m> is the entry in the top left and <m>d</m> is the entry in the bottom right.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a=1</m> and <m>d=4</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct!
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a=4</m> and <m>d=1</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              For a matrix described by <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
              the entry <m>a</m> is the entry in the top left and <m>d</m> is the entry in the bottom right.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>a=4</m> and <m>d=3</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              For a matrix described by <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
              the entry <m>a</m> is the entry in the top left and <m>d</m> is the entry in the bottom right.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      
      </choices>
    </task>
    <task label="partsof2by2matrix-b">>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Identify the values of <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> for the matrix <m>A</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>b=1</m> and <m>c=2</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              For a matrix described by <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
              the entry <m>b</m> is the entry in the top right and <m>c</m> is the entry in the bottom left.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>b=3</m> and <m>c=2</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              For a matrix described by <m>\begin{bmatrix} a \amp b \\ c \amp d \end{bmatrix}</m>, 
              the entry <m>b</m> is the entry in the top right and <m>c</m> is the entry in the bottom left.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>b=2</m> and <m>c=3</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct!
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>b=-2</m> and <m>c=-3</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Don't multiply them by <m>-1</m> like in the inverse, just identify what <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> are to start with.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>
    <task label="partsof2by2matrix-c">>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the value of <m>ad-bc</m> for the matrix <m>A</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>-2</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct! <m>a=1</m>, <m>d=4</m>, <m>b=2</m>, and <m>c=3</m>, so 
              <me>ad-bc=1\cdot 4 - 2\cdot 3 = 4-6 = -2</me>
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>2</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              <m>a=1</m>, <m>d=4</m>, <m>b=2</m>, and <m>c=3</m>, so 
              <me>ad-bc=1\cdot 4 - 2\cdot 3</me>
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>10</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              <m>a=1</m>, <m>d=4</m>, <m>b=2</m>, and <m>c=3</m>, so 
              <me>ad-bc=1\cdot 4 - 2\cdot 3</me>
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{-1}{2}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              <m>a=1</m>, <m>d=4</m>, <m>b=2</m>, and <m>c=3</m>, so 
              <me>ad-bc=1\cdot 4 - 2\cdot 3</me>
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>
    <task label="partsof2by2matrix-d">>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Which matrix below is <m>\begin{bmatrix} d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}</m> for the matrix <m>A</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix} -1 \amp 3 \\ 2 \amp -4 \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              To calculate <m>\begin{bmatrix} d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}</m>,
              you swap entries <m>a</m> and <m>d</m> and multiply entries <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> by negative 1.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix} -4 \amp -2 \\ -3 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              To calculate <m>\begin{bmatrix} d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}</m>,
              you swap entries <m>a</m> and <m>d</m> and multiply entries <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> by negative 1.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp -2 \\ -3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct!
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp -3 \\ -2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              To calculate <m>\begin{bmatrix} d \amp -b \\ -c \amp a \end{bmatrix}</m>,
              you swap entries <m>a</m> and <m>d</m> and multiply entries <m>b</m> and <m>c</m> by negative 1.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>
    <task label="partsof2by2matrix-e">>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Which of the matrices below is <m>A^{-1}</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp 1 \\ \frac{3}{2} \amp \frac{-1}{2} \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct!
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp -2 \\ -3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Don't forget to multiply by <m>\frac{1}{ad-bc}</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\frac{-1}{2}\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp -2 \\ -3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct!
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>-2\begin{bmatrix} 4 \amp -2 \\ -3 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Multiply by <m>\frac{1}{ad-bc}</m>, not <m>ad-bc</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>
   </exercise>
  <p>
    Let's see another example.
  </p>
    <example xml:id="ex_inverse_4"><title>Using the formula for <m>2\times 2</m> inverses </title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Calculate the inverse, if it exists, of
        <me>
          A = \left[\begin{array}{cc} 3 \amp  2\\-1 \amp  9 \end{array} \right]
        </me>.
        If <m>A^{-1}</m> exists, use it to solve the linear system
        <md>
          <mrow>3x + 2y \amp= 29 </mrow>
          <mrow>-x + 9y \amp= -29 </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        Since <m>ad-bc = 29 \neq 0</m>, we know <m>A^{-1}</m> exists and we calculate
        <md>
          <mrow>A^{-1} \amp = \frac{1}{3(9)-2(-1)}\left[\begin{array}{cc} 9\amp -2</mrow>
          <mrow>1\amp 3\end{array}\right]</mrow>
          <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{29}\left[\begin{array}{cc} 9\amp -2</mrow>
          <mrow>1\amp 3\end{array}\right]</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        We can leave our answer in this form, or we could multiply it out and get
        <me>
          A^{-1} = \frac{1}{29}\left[\begin{array}{cc} 9\amp -2\\1\amp 3 \end{array} \right] = \left[\begin{array}{cc}  9/29 \amp  -2/29\\1/29 \amp  3/29 \end{array} \right]
        </me>.
      </p>
      <p>
        To solve the system 
        <md>
          <mrow>3x + 2y \amp= 29 </mrow>
          <mrow>-x + 9y \amp= -29 </mrow>
        </md>,
        we write 
        <md>
          <mrow> \left[\begin{array}{cc} 3 \amp  2\\-1 \amp  9 \end{array} \right] \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 29 \\ -29 \end{bmatrix} \amp \amp \text{rewrite as a matrix equation} </mrow>
          <mrow> A \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 29 \\ -29 \end{bmatrix} \amp \amp \text{the matrix of coefficients is }A </mrow>
          <mrow> A^{-1}A \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = A^{-1}\begin{bmatrix} 29 \\ -29 \end{bmatrix} \amp \amp \text{multiply on the left by }A^{-1}</mrow>
          <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = \left[\begin{array}{cc}  9/29 \amp  -2/29\\1/29 \amp  3/29 \end{array} \right]\begin{bmatrix} 29 \\ -29 \end{bmatrix} \amp \amp \text{use what we calculated for } A^{-1} </mrow>
          <mrow> \begin{bmatrix}x \\ y \end{bmatrix} \amp = \begin{bmatrix} 11 \\ -2 \end{bmatrix} \amp \amp \text{multiply the matrices together}</mrow>
        </md>.
        We check that
        <md>
          <mrow>3\cdot 11 + 2(-2) \amp= 29 </mrow>
          <mrow>-11 + 9(-2) \amp= -29 </mrow>
        </md>
        and see that <m>x=11</m>, <m>y=-2</m> is indeed a solution to the given linear system.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
      
  
      
